	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Absor On New EverQuest.com Look</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=507266" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top">
		    <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    Yesterday, Absor <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000352.html">commented</a> on the look of the new offical Everquest website.  Here is what he had to say:<br>
<blockquote>
  I'm sure by now you've already seen the revamp of EverQuest.com.
  <p>One of the things I do here is try to keep my nose into the web development
  for EverQuest.com. We have some very talented web people and some fantastic
  artists working on the site. I know this because they're smart enough to
  ignore most of my ideas…
  <p>We'd really like to get some of your comments and suggestions about the
  site. But before you send in your comments, let me try to explain what it is
  that the new site is designed to do and a little of the logic behind how we're
  trying to do it.
  <p>When someone hears about EverQuest from their friends and is curious to
  learn more about the game, the first thing they are most likely to do when
  they get to their computer is to type <a href="http://www.everquest.com" target="_blank">www.everquest.com</a>
  into their browser. We want those new potential customers to be able to learn
  the basics about the game without the clutter and complication of the stuff
  that experienced players are interested in.
  <p>Those of you that post to and read the Developer's Corner are probably
  familiar with the old EverQuest.com. That site basically caters to the
  experienced player, it's where we talk about new features, gameplay and stuff
  like that. A lot of that information isn't really useful to a potential new
  customer. When I want to learn about a game, I want to see screenshots, I want
  to get a feel for it. That's what we're trying to achieve with EverQuest.com.
  I've read comments on the net suggesting that it is just a marketing site now.
  That's almost true. We certainly want it to be appealing to potential players
  without blasting them with complicated concepts like melee balance changes
  when they just want to see if they are interested in the game at all. We do
  indeed want to sell the game to potential players through EverQuest.com.
  <p>So we renamed the old EverQuest.com site, it is now EverQuest Live. For
  those of you that are experienced EverQuest players, EverQuest Live is
  probably the site you want to bookmark (www.everquestlive.com).
  <p>We're not done fiddling with the web site. I guess with an ongoing project
  like EverQuest we'll probably never be done adding things to the site. The web
  development folks have some really great ideas for the future of the site. But
  before we roll forward with new changes, we'd like to hear your comments about
  the changes we just made. So please reply to this thread with any comments or
  suggestions and I'll make certain that the web team sees them.
  <p>Thanks.
  <p>Alan<br>
  </p>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
